[HORSE SNORTS]

2
00:00:56,391 --> 00:00:58,893
WOMAN:
<i>The Oracle's words stand as a warning.</i>

3
00:00:59,602 --> 00:01:00,603
<i>A prophecy.</i>

4
00:01:02,522 --> 00:01:04,315
<i>Sparta will fall.</i>

5
00:01:04,816 --> 00:01:07,360
<i>All of Greece will fall.</i>

6
00:01:07,610 --> 00:01:09,445
[YELLING]

7
00:01:14,367 --> 00:01:17,996
<i>And Persian fire will reduce Athens to cinder.</i>

8
00:01:18,746 --> 00:01:21,291
<i>For Athens is a pile of stone and wood...</i>

9
00:01:21,541 --> 00:01:23,209
<i>...and cloth and dust...</i>

10
00:01:23,751 --> 00:01:27,422
<i>...and, as dust, will vanish into the wind.</i>

11
00:01:27,755 --> 00:01:30,300
<i>Only the Athenians themselves exist.</i>

12
00:01:30,550 --> 00:01:33,553
<i>And the fate of the world hangs
on their every syllable.</i>

13
00:01:40,476 --> 00:01:41,603
<i>Only the Athenians exist.</i>

14
00:01:43,688 --> 00:01:46,149
<i>And only stout wooden ships can save them.</i>

15
00:01:47,900 --> 00:01:49,569
<i>Wooden ships...</i>

16
00:01:50,153 --> 00:01:52,447
<i>...and a tidal wave of heroes' blood.</i>

17
00:02:02,040 --> 00:02:04,709
<i>Leonidas, my husband...</i>

18
00:02:05,418 --> 00:02:06,961
<i>...Leonidas, your king...</i>

19
00:02:08,630 --> 00:02:12,300
...Leonidas and the brave 300 are dead.

20
00:02:13,593 --> 00:02:15,219
The free men and women of Greece...

21
00:02:15,470 --> 00:02:18,222
...are not bound by
a beautiful Spartan death.

22
00:02:18,598 --> 00:02:20,600
War is not their love.

23
00:02:20,850 --> 00:02:23,186
Yet he lay down his life for them.

24
00:02:23,436 --> 00:02:25,396
For the promise Greece holds.

25
00:02:28,149 --> 00:02:32,153
'Tis our enemies who forged our freedom
in the fires of war.

26
00:02:33,279 --> 00:02:36,366
It was King Darius
who came to take our land.

27
00:02:37,450 --> 00:02:40,745
Ten years ago,
when youth still burned in our eyes...

28
00:02:41,079 --> 00:02:44,791
...before this bitter war forced our children
to become men.

29
00:02:46,417 --> 00:02:50,338
Ten years ago, this war began...

30
00:02:50,588 --> 00:02:52,590
...as all wars begin:

31
00:02:53,383 --> 00:02:55,218
With a grievance.

32
00:02:58,221 --> 00:02:59,722
<i>Marathon.</i>

33
00:03:01,140 --> 00:03:02,975
<i>The Persian king, Darius...</i>

34
00:03:03,476 --> 00:03:05,895
<i>...annoyed by the notion of Greek freedom...</i>

35
00:03:06,729 --> 00:03:09,065
<i>...has come to Greece to bring us to heel.</i>

36
00:03:11,609 --> 00:03:13,695
<i>He makes landfall at the field of Marathon...</i>

37
00:03:13,945 --> 00:03:16,364
<i>...with an invading force
which outnumbers...</i>

38
00:03:16,614 --> 00:03:18,574
<i>...the Greek defenders three-to-one.</i>

39
00:03:18,825 --> 00:03:21,953
<i>And so at dawn, the hopeless Athenians
do the unthinkable.</i>

40
00:03:22,745 --> 00:03:24,247
<i>They attack.</i>

41
00:03:24,497 --> 00:03:26,874
<i>They attack the weary Persians
as they disembark...</i>

42
00:03:27,125 --> 00:03:30,586
<i>...their ships
on shaky legs after a month at sea.</i>

43
00:03:31,546 --> 00:03:34,048
<i>They attack before they can
establish their war camp...</i>

44
00:03:34,298 --> 00:03:35,758
<i>...and supply their soldiers.</i>

45
00:03:36,759 --> 00:03:37,760
<i>And who...</i>

46
00:03:38,010 --> 00:03:40,388
<i>...is the architect of this mad strategy?</i>

47
00:03:41,013 --> 00:03:41,973
<i>A little-known Athenian...</i>

48
00:03:42,223 --> 00:03:43,725
<i>...soldier.</i>

49
00:03:44,642 --> 00:03:46,227
<i>His men call him...</i>

50
00:03:46,477 --> 00:03:48,271
<i>...Themistokles.</i>

51
00:03:48,521 --> 00:03:52,108
<i>He gives the Persians a taste
of Athenian shock combat.</i>

52
00:03:52,358 --> 00:03:53,359
[THEMISTOKLES YELLS]

53
00:03:53,609 --> 00:03:55,194
[ALL YELLING AND GRUNTING]

54
00:05:00,760 --> 00:05:01,803
[HORSES NEIGHING]

55
00:05:15,525 --> 00:05:17,360
[HORSE NEIGHING]

56
00:05:49,767 --> 00:05:51,769
[ALL SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

57
00:05:56,899 --> 00:05:57,608
[YELLS]

58
00:06:03,573 --> 00:06:05,491
[YELLS]

59
00:06:14,584 --> 00:06:16,168
GORGO:
<i>All thoughts of glory are gone.</i>

60
00:06:17,753 --> 00:06:18,713
<i>Thousands dead.</i>

61
00:06:19,422 --> 00:06:20,965
<i>Hundreds of them their own.</i>

62
00:06:23,885 --> 00:06:27,305
<i>All for an idea: A free Greece...</i>

63
00:06:27,555 --> 00:06:30,474
<i>...an Athenian experiment
called "democracy."</i>

64
00:06:34,103 --> 00:06:35,396
<i>Could this idea be worth it?</i>

65
00:06:36,606 --> 00:06:39,317
<i>Worth all this sacrifice?</i>

66
00:06:41,402 --> 00:06:43,738
<i>Themistokles would let
the good King Darius decide.</i>

67
00:06:47,033 --> 00:06:48,659
<i>For through the chaos...</i>

68
00:06:48,910 --> 00:06:50,453
<i>...a moment appeared.</i>

69
00:06:53,998 --> 00:06:55,666
<i>And Themistokles would seize it.</i>

70
00:07:06,886 --> 00:07:07,929
<i>A moment...</i>

71
00:07:08,179 --> 00:07:09,972
<i>...that would ring across the centuries.</i>

72
00:07:10,222 --> 00:07:11,223
<i>A moment that would...</i>

73
00:07:11,474 --> 00:07:13,225
<i>...raise him from simple soldier...</i>

74
00:07:13,476 --> 00:07:15,645
<i>...to the height of Athenian political power.</i>

75
00:07:15,895 --> 00:07:18,439
No!

76
00:07:20,858 --> 00:07:24,278
<i>A moment that would make
Themistokles a legend.</i>

77
00:07:43,047 --> 00:07:44,674
<i>Yet even as the praise and glory...</i>

78
00:07:44,924 --> 00:07:46,759
<i>...were heaped upon him...</i>

79
00:07:47,009 --> 00:07:49,929
<i>...Themistokles knew in his heart
he had made a mistake.</i>

80
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:53,808
<i>It was Darius' son, Xerxes...</i>

81
00:07:54,058 --> 00:07:56,477
<i>...whose eyes had the stink
of destiny about them.</i>

82
00:07:58,562 --> 00:08:01,065
<i>Themistokles knew
he should have killed that boy.</i>

83
00:08:02,942 --> 00:08:06,028
<i>That glorious mistake
would forever haunt him.</i>

84
00:08:12,326 --> 00:08:14,036
<i>And so it was Themistokles himself...</i>

85
00:08:14,286 --> 00:08:17,373
<i>...who sent a ripple
across the Persian empire...</i>

86
00:08:17,623 --> 00:08:19,333
<i>...and set into motion...</i>

87
00:08:19,583 --> 00:08:22,294
<i>...forces that would bring fire
to the heart of Greece.</i>

88
00:08:25,006 --> 00:08:26,924
<i>For as the good king lay dying...</i>

89
00:08:27,174 --> 00:08:28,634
<i>...all his greatest generals...</i>

90
00:08:28,884 --> 00:08:31,887
<i>...and advisors
were summoned to his bedside.</i>

91
00:08:32,221 --> 00:08:33,389
<i>None greater...</i>

92
00:08:33,639 --> 00:08:37,351
<i>...than his finest
naval commander, Artemisia.</i>

93
00:08:37,768 --> 00:08:40,438
<i>Her ferocity bested only by her beauty.</i>

94
00:08:40,688 --> 00:08:43,941
<i>Her beauty matched only
by her devotion to her king.</i>

95
00:08:50,072 --> 00:08:52,324
<i>Darius favored Artemisia
among his generals...</i>

96
00:08:52,575 --> 00:08:55,494
<i>...for she had brought him victory
on the battlefield.</i>

97
00:08:56,120 --> 00:08:57,288
<i>In her...</i>

98
00:08:57,538 --> 00:09:00,458
<i>...he had the perfect warrior protégée...</i>

99
00:09:00,708 --> 00:09:02,626
<i>...that his son, Xerxes, would never be.</i>

100
00:09:06,839 --> 00:09:10,217
DARIUS [IN STRAINED VOICE]:
So sweet, my child.

101
00:09:11,218 --> 00:09:13,012
My sweet...

102
00:09:13,763 --> 00:09:15,389
...child.

103
00:09:23,773 --> 00:09:25,274
XERXES:
Father.

104
00:09:25,983 --> 00:09:27,526
Xerxes.

105
00:09:28,027 --> 00:09:31,405
Do not repeat your father's mistake.

106
00:09:32,740 --> 00:09:36,410
Leave the ignoble Greeks to their ways.

107
00:09:37,536 --> 00:09:40,664
Only the gods can defeat them.

108
00:09:41,582 --> 00:09:44,668
Only the gods.

109
00:09:56,722 --> 00:09:58,766
GORGO:
<i>For seven days, Xerxes mourned...</i>

110
00:09:59,016 --> 00:10:01,102
<i>...paralyzed by grief.</i>

111
00:10:01,352 --> 00:10:04,688
<i>On the eighth day, Artemisia
whispered the seed of madness...</i>

112
00:10:04,939 --> 00:10:06,690
<i>...that would consume him.</i>

113
00:10:06,941 --> 00:10:10,694
[WHISPERING]
Your father's words were not a warning...

114
00:10:11,487 --> 00:10:13,114
...but a challenge.

115
00:10:14,615 --> 00:10:17,535
Only the gods can defeat the Greeks?

116
00:10:20,121 --> 00:10:24,125
You will be a god-king.

117
00:10:28,462 --> 00:10:30,756
GORGO:
<i>Artemisia gathered the priests, wizards...</i>

118
00:10:31,006 --> 00:10:34,093
<i>...and mystics
from every corner of the empire.</i>

119
00:10:34,510 --> 00:10:35,636
<i>They wrapped...</i>

120
00:10:35,886 --> 00:10:39,265
<i>...the young king in Cimmerian gauze
dipped in ancient potions...</i>

121
00:10:39,682 --> 00:10:42,059
<i>...and set him to wander the desert...</i>

122
00:10:43,269 --> 00:10:46,522
<i>...till in a delirium of heat and thirst,
he stumbled upon...</i>

123
00:10:46,772 --> 00:10:48,149
<i>...a hermit's cave.</i>

124
00:10:52,111 --> 00:10:54,655
<i>Xerxes passed the vacant eyes...</i>

125
00:10:54,905 --> 00:10:56,323
<i>...and empty souls...</i>

126
00:10:56,574 --> 00:11:00,578
<i>...of the hollow creatures that dwell
in the dark corners of all men's hearts.</i>

127
00:11:03,164 --> 00:11:05,291
<i>And in that darkness...</i>

128
00:11:06,625 --> 00:11:08,460
<i>...he surrendered himself completely...</i>

129
00:11:08,711 --> 00:11:11,755
<i>...to power so evil and perverse...</i>

130
00:11:15,384 --> 00:11:17,094
<i>...that, as he emerged...</i>

131
00:11:17,344 --> 00:11:20,681
<i>...no part of a human man
that was Xerxes survived.</i>

132
00:11:29,315 --> 00:11:32,526
<i>His eyes blazed like scarlet coals.</i>

133
00:11:34,403 --> 00:11:38,324
<i>He was stripped, cleansed, glabrous...</i>

134
00:11:38,574 --> 00:11:40,075
<i>...and smooth.</i>

135
00:11:41,994 --> 00:11:43,245
<i>Xerxes was reborn...</i>

136
00:11:43,495 --> 00:11:44,955
<i>...a god.</i>

137
00:11:50,294 --> 00:11:52,463
<i>Artemisia trusted no one.</i>

138
00:11:53,172 --> 00:11:55,049
<i>So in the cover of night...</i>

139
00:11:55,299 --> 00:11:59,053
<i>...the palace was cleansed
of all Xerxes' allies.</i>

140
00:12:02,389 --> 00:12:04,099
<i>All those he trusted...</i>

141
00:12:08,771 --> 00:12:11,023
<i>...all those who had raised him...</i>

142
00:12:15,819 --> 00:12:18,155
<i>...all those he had
once looked to for counsel...</i>

143
00:12:19,990 --> 00:12:22,743
<i>...were quickly introduced to her wrath.</i>

144
00:12:45,182 --> 00:12:47,184
[CROWD CHEERING]

145
00:12:48,477 --> 00:12:49,979
<i>And as the god-king stood...</i>

146
00:12:50,229 --> 00:12:51,897
<i>...before his people...</i>

147
00:12:53,065 --> 00:12:55,901
<i>...Artemisia watched her flawless
manipulation take shape.</i>

148
00:12:56,151 --> 00:12:58,904
- For glory's sake...
ARTEMISIA [WHISPERING]: For glory's sake...

149
00:12:59,154 --> 00:13:01,740
- ...for vengeance's sake...
- ...for vengeance's sake...

150
00:13:03,993 --> 00:13:05,286
...war.

151
00:13:05,869 --> 00:13:07,288
...war!

152
00:13:07,538 --> 00:13:09,540
[CROWD CHEERING]

153
00:13:10,082 --> 00:13:12,626
GORGO:
<i>War is coming to Greece...</i>

154
00:13:12,876 --> 00:13:16,380
<i>...in the visage of a monster army
over a million strong.</i>

155
00:13:17,256 --> 00:13:20,467
<i>It should be little more than a formality
for Themistokles...</i>

156
00:13:20,718 --> 00:13:22,386
<i>...the hero of Marathon...</i>

157
00:13:22,636 --> 00:13:24,596
<i>...to finish what he began.</i>

158
00:13:25,889 --> 00:13:29,435
Please! We must appeal to Xerxes' reason!

159
00:13:29,685 --> 00:13:30,728
MAN 1:
Coward!

160
00:13:30,978 --> 00:13:33,230
Athens is a city of cowards!

161
00:13:33,480 --> 00:13:34,023
Shut your cock hole!

162
00:13:34,273 --> 00:13:35,357
Shut your own!

163
00:13:35,607 --> 00:13:37,568
I'll kill you! Fuck the Spartans!

164
00:13:37,818 --> 00:13:39,445
Fuck those muscle-bound boy-lovers!

165
00:13:39,695 --> 00:13:40,404
Silence!

166
00:13:40,654 --> 00:13:42,197
MAN 2:
Silence for the hero of Marathon!

167
00:13:42,448 --> 00:13:44,950
THEMISTOKLES:
This is a democracy, not a street fight.

168
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,994
MAN 3:
Quiet! It's Themistokles.

169
00:13:47,244 --> 00:13:50,831
The Persian attack will come
from both the north and the south.

170
00:13:51,081 --> 00:13:53,667
The city-states should negotiate a truce.

171
00:13:53,917 --> 00:13:56,295
Yes, yes, we must negotiate.

172
00:13:57,296 --> 00:13:58,881
THEMISTOKLES:
Negotiate with tyranny?

173
00:14:00,090 --> 00:14:02,968
Give me one example of when
that has ever profited a nation.

174
00:14:03,218 --> 00:14:06,055
MAN 4: You're right. We must unite.
THEMISTOKLES: My fellow countrymen...

175
00:14:06,764 --> 00:14:09,433
...we can only judge the future...

176
00:14:09,683 --> 00:14:12,353
...from what we have suffered in the past.

177
00:14:13,729 --> 00:14:16,357
Now, many of you here
stood with me at Marathon.

178
00:14:17,524 --> 00:14:19,526
And for those of you who served...

179
00:14:19,777 --> 00:14:21,904
...and faced the cut
and thrust of battle...

180
00:14:22,154 --> 00:14:24,698
...you know how true peace is forged.

181
00:14:25,616 --> 00:14:27,326
Do not be deceived.

182
00:14:27,576 --> 00:14:29,620
Xerxes, the son of Darius...

183
00:14:29,870 --> 00:14:31,955
...is a wolf at our door.

184
00:14:32,748 --> 00:14:34,917
Right here, right now...

185
00:14:35,793 --> 00:14:37,503
...we must choose:

186
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:40,589
Do we stand and fight for Greece or not?

187
00:14:41,757 --> 00:14:42,925
Argos...

188
00:14:43,175 --> 00:14:44,343
...Corinth...

189
00:14:44,593 --> 00:14:45,761
...Megara...

190
00:14:46,011 --> 00:14:47,638
...Athens.

191
00:14:47,888 --> 00:14:50,349
Not even Sparta
can match the Persians alone.

192
00:14:50,599 --> 00:14:52,810
We must persevere as one nation.

193
00:14:53,060 --> 00:14:55,312
Or we will perish clinging onto...

194
00:14:55,562 --> 00:14:57,231
...our own self-interests.

195
00:14:58,357 --> 00:15:01,693
Send us the ships that we need
to defend Greece.

196
00:15:01,944 --> 00:15:04,363
Themistokles will need more
than our cities' ships.

197
00:15:04,613 --> 00:15:06,532
He will need our children
to join the fight.

198
00:15:06,782 --> 00:15:08,409
[CROWD MURMURS]

199
00:15:08,659 --> 00:15:10,035
And what of Sparta?

200
00:15:10,285 --> 00:15:13,122
You send every ship that we have...

201
00:15:13,372 --> 00:15:15,707
...to the northern coast of Euboea.

202
00:15:16,959 --> 00:15:20,838
I will go and seek the help
of the great Spartans.

203
00:15:21,088 --> 00:15:22,673
[CROWD MURMURING]

204
00:15:42,484 --> 00:15:43,485
ARTEMISIA:
Still no word...

205
00:15:43,735 --> 00:15:46,196
...from the messenger
you sent to Sparta.

206
00:15:46,864 --> 00:15:49,992
King Leonidas may have been insulted
by your generous offer.

207
00:15:50,242 --> 00:15:54,204
Perhaps I need to march into Sparta myself
and burn it to the ground.

208
00:15:56,165 --> 00:15:57,666
Remember...

209
00:15:57,916 --> 00:15:59,626
...when a king is loved as I am...

210
00:16:01,086 --> 00:16:03,338
...much can be accomplished.

211
00:16:04,882 --> 00:16:08,218
They would be fools
to resist my divine power.

212
00:16:08,469 --> 00:16:11,263
Athens is attempting to assemble a coalition.

213
00:16:11,513 --> 00:16:13,974
It'll be nothing more
than a patchwork of ships.

214
00:16:16,185 --> 00:16:19,980
Once these waters have been traversed,
I will lead my force across the land.

215
00:16:20,230 --> 00:16:22,566
I will remind the cowards of Greece...

216
00:16:22,816 --> 00:16:26,236
...that we have not forgotten their insolence.

217
00:16:36,163 --> 00:16:37,956
Rest and water the horses.

218
00:16:38,207 --> 00:16:39,625
It's best I go alone.

219
00:16:39,875 --> 00:16:43,295
Spartans don't get along well with others.

220
00:16:46,298 --> 00:16:47,299
[GRUNTING]

221
00:17:04,107 --> 00:17:05,734
[MEN GRUNTING IN UNISON]

222
00:17:32,970 --> 00:17:33,554
[GROANS]

223
00:17:34,763 --> 00:17:36,557
- Spartans.
DILIOS: Themistokles.

224
00:17:37,933 --> 00:17:39,393
You old snake.

225
00:17:39,643 --> 00:17:42,479
- What brings you this far south?
- I've come to see Leonidas.

226
00:17:42,729 --> 00:17:45,649
- To warn him that the Persians are on the march.
- You're too late.

227
00:17:45,899 --> 00:17:49,069
Persian messenger already presented
his terms to Leonidas.

228
00:17:49,820 --> 00:17:52,197
Symbolic offering of earth and water.

229
00:18:00,831 --> 00:18:02,207
Spartans!

230
00:18:02,457 --> 00:18:03,500
Know this and know it well.

231
00:18:03,750 --> 00:18:04,751
[COUGHS]

232
00:18:05,002 --> 00:18:07,588
That any Spartan's finest moment...

233
00:18:08,338 --> 00:18:09,756
...the greatest fulfillment...

234
00:18:10,007 --> 00:18:11,842
...of all he holds dear...

235
00:18:12,092 --> 00:18:13,385
...is that moment...

236
00:18:13,635 --> 00:18:15,762
...when he has fought his heart out...

237
00:18:16,013 --> 00:18:18,849
...for the preservation of Sparta...

238
00:18:19,099 --> 00:18:22,436
...and lies dead on the battlefield...

239
00:18:22,686 --> 00:18:24,396
...victorious.

240
00:18:26,189 --> 00:18:27,441
Now...

241
00:18:27,941 --> 00:18:29,985
...who is willing to die at our king's side?

242
00:18:30,235 --> 00:18:31,361
MEN [IN UNISON]:
Ah-ooh!

243
00:18:31,612 --> 00:18:33,864
Ah-ooh! Ah-ooh!

244
00:18:34,489 --> 00:18:36,074
GORGO:
Themistokles.

245
00:18:38,035 --> 00:18:41,955
You've come a long way to stroke your cock
whilst watching real men train.

246
00:18:42,205 --> 00:18:43,248
THEMISTOKLES:
Queen Gorgo.

247
00:18:44,416 --> 00:18:47,377
Shouldn't he be training them
to live at their king's side?

248
00:18:48,962 --> 00:18:50,255
THEMISTOKLES:
<i>A new age is dawning, Gorgo.</i>

249
00:18:52,257 --> 00:18:56,094
Won't be long before men rise up
and shed the yoke of mysticism and tyranny.

250
00:18:56,345 --> 00:18:58,805
