by the finest warriors of the Persian empire...</i>

354
00:27:12,924 --> 00:27:14,384
<i>...until no match could be found...</i>

355
00:27:14,634 --> 00:27:15,844
<i>...for her skills and gift with the sword.</i>

356
00:27:44,080 --> 00:27:46,583
<i>The great King Darius was impressed
by her commitment.</i>

357
00:27:47,876 --> 00:27:50,086
<i>And she quickly rose to command
at his side.</i>

358
00:27:53,840 --> 00:27:55,466
AESKYLOS:
<i>She has sold her soul...</i>

359
00:27:55,717 --> 00:27:57,177
...to Death himself.

360
00:27:58,511 --> 00:28:00,847
Well, some could say
that I've sold mine to Greece.

361
00:28:05,101 --> 00:28:06,102
And what do you think?

362
00:28:06,352 --> 00:28:08,062
- Me?
THEMISTOKLES: Yes.

363
00:28:08,313 --> 00:28:10,190
You are the future of this country.

364
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:12,609
I'm ready to fight.

365
00:28:13,610 --> 00:28:15,028
[THEMISTOKLES CHUCKLES]

366
00:28:16,112 --> 00:28:18,573
I like him. He reminds me of you.

367
00:28:19,365 --> 00:28:20,033
AESKYLOS:
We will need...

368
00:28:20,283 --> 00:28:21,075
...every last man.

369
00:28:21,326 --> 00:28:22,410
He is still just a boy.

370
00:28:22,660 --> 00:28:23,995
Much younger...

371
00:28:24,245 --> 00:28:26,039
- ...have defended our country.
- Enough!

372
00:28:26,497 --> 00:28:29,250
You are a dreamer
and will speak of this no more.

373
00:28:33,087 --> 00:28:35,089
Themistokles, I've set your plan in motion.

374
00:28:35,340 --> 00:28:38,259
And my land force
will be assembled by the second day.

375
00:28:38,509 --> 00:28:41,346
You will be needed.
I can assure you of that.

376
00:28:45,141 --> 00:28:47,060
And there is bad news.

377
00:28:47,310 --> 00:28:50,271
Leonidas has marched north
to the Hot Gates.

378
00:28:52,065 --> 00:28:54,025
AESKYLOS:
<i>Bad news? With the Spartans...</i>

379
00:28:54,275 --> 00:28:58,112
<i>- ...at the Hot Gates, our victory is assured.</i>
SCYLLIAS: <i>If the army were with him.</i>

380
00:28:59,113 --> 00:29:01,032
<i>But between the Oracle and the Carneia...</i>

381
00:29:01,282 --> 00:29:03,910
<i>...Leonidas has marched to Thermopylae
with just 300 men.</i>

382
00:29:05,078 --> 00:29:08,539
AESKYLOS:
<i>So the only thing standing between Athens...</i>

383
00:29:08,790 --> 00:29:10,291
<i>...and total annihilation...</i>

384
00:29:11,334 --> 00:29:13,920
<i>...is Leonidas and 300 Spartans.</i>

385
00:29:18,758 --> 00:29:20,843
AESKYLOS:
I will search out the veterans among them.

386
00:29:21,094 --> 00:29:23,846
- Establish some order among the volunteers.
THEMISTOKLES: Good.

387
00:29:24,555 --> 00:29:27,684
There's little time
to teach these farmhands strategy.

388
00:29:28,268 --> 00:29:30,311
Just keep them well fed...

389
00:29:31,271 --> 00:29:32,647
...and sober.

390
00:29:33,314 --> 00:29:34,732
AESKYLOS:
Anything else?

391
00:29:35,275 --> 00:29:37,193
Wouldn't hurt if they could
swing a sword.

392
00:29:40,113 --> 00:29:41,823
Well, I'll be damned.

393
00:29:43,283 --> 00:29:44,284
Shit.

394
00:29:44,534 --> 00:29:47,453
- Does your father know that you're here?
- No, sir.

395
00:29:47,704 --> 00:29:49,747
And this shield and sword?

396
00:29:49,998 --> 00:29:51,499
My grandfather's.

397
00:29:51,749 --> 00:29:54,544
My mother entrusted them to me
this morning.

398
00:29:55,044 --> 00:29:58,339
- When she gave you her blessing?
CALISTO: Yes, sir.

399
00:29:58,965 --> 00:30:01,217
With a sharp blade, no less.

400
00:30:03,011 --> 00:30:05,847
Your father is preparing a surprise
for our enemy tomorrow.

401
00:30:06,097 --> 00:30:09,434
I choose to fight here. Now.

402
00:30:11,519 --> 00:30:13,271
Come aboard my ship.

403
00:30:13,896 --> 00:30:15,273
That is where you will fight.

404
00:30:15,523 --> 00:30:16,774
Yes, sir.

405
00:30:21,070 --> 00:30:22,322
COMMANDER 1:
We've just over 50 ships.

406
00:30:22,572 --> 00:30:25,325
Persian forces reported a number
in the thousands.

407
00:30:25,575 --> 00:30:28,911
- Those ships appear hardly seaworthy.
COMMANDER 1: Nothing like the monster ships...

408
00:30:29,162 --> 00:30:32,457
- ...of the Persian fleet.
- We have the advantage. Speed, maneuverability.

409
00:30:32,749 --> 00:30:36,461
The rest of the city-states have sent
anywhere from a handful to a single ship.

410
00:30:36,711 --> 00:30:40,006
- Of course, Athens supplied the balance.
COMMANDER 2: We have report...

411
00:30:40,256 --> 00:30:44,260
...a small advance force of Persian ships have
taken refuge from the storm across the strait.

412
00:30:44,552 --> 00:30:46,846
If the weather breaks,
we could hit them at dawn.

413
00:30:48,723 --> 00:30:49,766
An early Greek victory.

414
00:30:50,016 --> 00:30:51,809
COMMANDER 1:
The gods have given us an opportunity...

415
00:30:52,060 --> 00:30:54,020
...to wound the Persians,
strengthen Greek morale.

416
00:30:56,189 --> 00:30:57,315
A tempting distraction.

417
00:30:57,565 --> 00:30:59,650
But we'll stick to the battle plan.

418
00:30:59,901 --> 00:31:03,029
Today at sundown, we will sail out
to meet the main Persian fleet.

419
00:31:03,279 --> 00:31:06,324
We'll attack in the open water
with no shore to narrow the battle.

420
00:31:06,574 --> 00:31:08,409
COMMANDER 2:
To attack a force of over 1000 ships...

421
00:31:08,659 --> 00:31:10,453
...with our meager force is suicide.

422
00:31:11,996 --> 00:31:13,956
Such is my plan.

423
00:31:18,127 --> 00:31:20,713
ARTAPHERNES:
Look at their excuse for a navy.

424
00:31:21,589 --> 00:31:23,966
ARTEMISIA:
Their ships are of little threat.

425
00:31:24,842 --> 00:31:27,095
I need a second in command, Artaphernes.

426
00:31:27,345 --> 00:31:31,349
And whoever proves their excellence
will earn a place beside me.

427
00:31:32,767 --> 00:31:35,603
General Bandari has offered
to lead the first attack.

428
00:31:35,853 --> 00:31:37,063
Bandari.

429
00:31:39,857 --> 00:31:40,942
Commander.

430
00:31:41,192 --> 00:31:43,111
If I let you lead our first offensive...

431
00:31:43,361 --> 00:31:46,406
...what guarantee do I have
that you'll bring me a quick victory?

432
00:31:46,656 --> 00:31:48,574
BANDARI:
My word and my life.

433
00:31:49,158 --> 00:31:50,159
Good.

434
00:31:50,701 --> 00:31:52,245
My rules of engagement?

435
00:31:52,870 --> 00:31:56,541
Humiliate the Greeks
and lay waste to their tiny ships.

436
00:31:57,542 --> 00:31:59,961
BANDARI:
They'll be dead to the last man.

437
00:32:10,596 --> 00:32:12,223
THEMISTOKLES:
My brothers.

438
00:32:12,723 --> 00:32:14,725
Steady your hearts.

439
00:32:16,561 --> 00:32:18,229
Look deep into your souls.

440
00:32:22,483 --> 00:32:25,570
For your mettle is to be tested this day.

441
00:32:29,407 --> 00:32:31,659
<i>If in the heat of battle...</i>

442
00:32:33,035 --> 00:32:35,705
<i>...you need a reason to fight on...</i>

443
00:32:36,831 --> 00:32:39,542
<i>...an idea for which you will give up...</i>

444
00:32:40,168 --> 00:32:42,420
...all that you will ever have...

445
00:32:43,629 --> 00:32:46,591
...you need only to look at the man
who fights at your side.

446
00:32:48,551 --> 00:32:51,053
This is the "why" of battle.

447
00:32:51,304 --> 00:32:54,098
This is the brotherhood of men-at-arms.

448
00:32:55,141 --> 00:32:56,601
<i>An unbreakable bond...</i>

449
00:32:56,851 --> 00:32:59,854
<i>...made stronger by the crucible of combat.</i>

450
00:33:01,314 --> 00:33:05,067
<i>You will never be closer than with those
who you shed your blood with.</i>

451
00:33:07,028 --> 00:33:09,113
<i>For there is no nobler cause...</i>

452
00:33:09,363 --> 00:33:12,700
<i>...than to fight for those
who will lay down their life for you.</i>

453
00:33:14,702 --> 00:33:17,121
So you fight strong today.

454
00:33:18,247 --> 00:33:20,333
You fight for your brothers.

455
00:33:21,626 --> 00:33:23,669
Fight for your families.

456
00:33:24,462 --> 00:33:26,464
Most of all, you fight for Greece!

457
00:33:26,714 --> 00:33:27,673
ALL:
Greece!

458
00:33:27,924 --> 00:33:28,549
[ALL SHOUT]

459
00:33:28,799 --> 00:33:29,800
Yeah!

460
00:33:32,011 --> 00:33:35,306
And there is only one thing to make sure of
when the fighting starts.

461
00:33:35,556 --> 00:33:36,599
What's that?

462
00:33:37,683 --> 00:33:39,435
Don't get killed on the first day.

463
00:33:39,685 --> 00:33:40,770
[MEN LAUGH]

464
00:33:41,020 --> 00:33:43,231
That goes for the rest of you.

465
00:34:14,929 --> 00:34:15,680
Persian ships...

466
00:34:15,930 --> 00:34:17,431
...are strong at the front.

467
00:34:17,682 --> 00:34:18,683
But they are weak...

468
00:34:18,933 --> 00:34:20,351
...in the middle.

469
00:34:20,601 --> 00:34:22,436
We attack them there.

470
00:34:32,697 --> 00:34:34,365
Now!

471
00:34:39,745 --> 00:34:42,331
[GRUNTING]

472
00:34:55,386 --> 00:34:56,470
Attack!

473
00:35:07,273 --> 00:35:08,065
[YELLING]

474
00:35:13,112 --> 00:35:13,696
[SCREAMING]

475
00:35:20,369 --> 00:35:20,953
[YELLING]

476
00:35:24,665 --> 00:35:26,042
Ram them!

477
00:35:36,969 --> 00:35:40,056
COMMANDER:
Archers, now! Now!

478
00:35:44,852 --> 00:35:45,895
[ALL YELL]

479
00:35:49,315 --> 00:35:50,775
Reverse!

480
00:35:51,108 --> 00:35:52,526
Now!

481
00:35:59,325 --> 00:36:00,701
Go through them!

482
00:36:10,336 --> 00:36:11,379
[MEN YELL]

483
00:36:29,021 --> 00:36:30,147
[MEN SCREAMING]

484
00:36:55,589 --> 00:36:56,841
ARTEMISIA:
The enemy's tactics...

485
00:36:57,091 --> 00:36:58,467
...are creative.

486
00:36:58,718 --> 00:37:01,137
The defensive circle
leaves no front to assault.

487
00:37:01,721 --> 00:37:03,097
We are losing.

488
00:37:03,347 --> 00:37:05,015
No, you are losing.

489
00:37:11,480 --> 00:37:12,857
Pull back.

490
00:37:13,357 --> 00:37:15,025
Let them have this day.

491
00:37:15,651 --> 00:37:18,696
I'm bored with your failures, Bandari.

492
00:37:23,868 --> 00:37:25,911
I'll not let this wound slow me.

493
00:37:26,162 --> 00:37:28,414
Heh. Somehow I believe you.

494
00:37:28,664 --> 00:37:30,875
My blade will be sharp and ready
by the morning.

495
00:37:31,876 --> 00:37:34,545
Good. Tomorrow you will fight
alongside your father.

496
00:37:36,630 --> 00:37:37,631
Not bad...

497
00:37:37,882 --> 00:37:41,343
- ...for a bunch of farmers.
- And poets and sculptors.

498
00:37:41,594 --> 00:37:43,053
Who'd have known untrained men...

499
00:37:43,304 --> 00:37:46,098
...would do so well against
such a considerable adversary?

500
00:37:48,476 --> 00:37:51,729
We're going to need all of our strength
for tomorrow's fight.

501
00:37:52,354 --> 00:37:54,565
How long do you think we can hold them?

502
00:37:57,526 --> 00:37:59,779
If my plan is to work...

503
00:38:01,614 --> 00:38:04,658
...long enough for the Spartans
to unite Greece.

504
00:38:05,951 --> 00:38:07,244
Men!

505
00:38:07,787 --> 00:38:09,121
Who will share their wine with me?

506
00:38:09,371 --> 00:38:11,499
[MEN SHOUT]

507
00:38:22,968 --> 00:38:24,053
Report.

508
00:38:24,303 --> 00:38:26,096
We are still tallying the losses.

509
00:38:26,722 --> 00:38:29,308
But you must understand,
it is extremely difficult...

510
00:38:29,558 --> 00:38:31,894
...given the sea and the darkness...

511
00:38:32,144 --> 00:38:33,729
...to get an accurate--

512
00:38:33,979 --> 00:38:35,523
[GRUNTS]

513
00:38:44,949 --> 00:38:46,075
Report?

514
00:38:46,700 --> 00:38:48,118
ARTAPHERNES:
Seventy-five ships lost.

515
00:38:48,369 --> 00:38:49,745
Thirty damaged beyond repair.

516
00:38:49,995 --> 00:38:53,040
Twenty could return with a few weeks' work
in a safe harbor.

517
00:38:57,211 --> 00:39:00,130
The commander of the Greek force
is named Themistokles.

518
00:39:00,381 --> 00:39:02,383
Yes, he is an Athenian general.

519
00:39:03,217 --> 00:39:05,052
He's rumored to have loosed the arrow...

520
00:39:05,302 --> 00:39:07,847
...that felled the great King Darius himself.

521
00:39:20,401 --> 00:39:22,361
No!

522
00:39:37,001 --> 00:39:41,005
This Themistokles has shown himself
to be quite brilliant in battle.

523
00:39:42,631 --> 00:39:44,717
Which is more than I can say for any of you.

524
00:39:46,093 --> 00:39:49,305
Do you gentlemen find my command
unreasonable?

525
00:39:49,763 --> 00:39:52,308
Is it too much to ask for victory?

526
00:39:52,558 --> 00:39:54,310
Your disappointment in yesterday's losses...

527
00:39:54,560 --> 00:39:56,145
...is warranted.

528
00:39:57,605 --> 00:39:59,607
My disappointment.

529
00:40:00,941 --> 00:40:03,360
My disappointment is not with my losses.

530
00:40:03,611 --> 00:40:07,239
The meager number of damaged ships
and dead slaves means nothing to me.

531
00:40:07,489 --> 00:40:11,285
No, my disappointment...

532
00:40:13,829 --> 00:40:15,539
...is in these men.

533
00:40:16,832 --> 00:40:17,833
For though I stand...

534
00:40:18,083 --> 00:40:20,169
...among 10,000...

535
00:40:20,502 --> 00:40:21,962
...I am alone.

536
00:40:24,048 --> 00:40:27,426
I long for a soul
who would stand by my side.

537
00:40:27,676 --> 00:40:28,844
Who I could trust.

538
00:40:34,892 --> 00:40:37,186
Tell me, General Kashani.

539
00:40:37,811 --> 00:40:39,647
Are you that man?

540
00:40:41,523 --> 00:40:44,777
You will taste your victory by the day's end.

541
00:40:45,235 --> 00:40:47,571
I will make certain of it.

542
00:40:48,822 --> 00:40:50,616
I hope so.

543
00:41:24,692 --> 00:41:26,694
[ALL GRUNTING]

544
00:42:22,207 --> 00:42:24,376
Advance!

545
00:42:31,508 --> 00:42:35,054
Now!

546
00:42:58,744 --> 00:43:01,038
Don't lose sight of them.

547
00:43:15,385 --> 00:43:16,512
The Greeks are retreating.

548
00:43:16,762 --> 00:43:19,223
ARTEMISIA:
He's got him right where he wants him.

549
00:43:19,473 --> 00:43:21,350
Kashani is a fine tactician.

550
00:43:21,975 --> 00:43:24,645
I was speaking of Themistokles.

551
00:43:34,488 --> 00:43:35,531
Rocks!

552
00:43:38,700 --> 00:43:40,202
Stop, stop!

553
00:43:40,452 --> 00:43:41,745
Stop!

554
00:43:42,454 --> 00:43:44,164
Brace yourselves!

555
00:43:46,959 --> 00:43:48,585
[ALL YELLING]

556
00:44:11,275 --> 00:44:13,277
[YELLING]

557
00:44:20,325 --> 00:44:21,618
[YELLS]

558
00:44:21,869 --> 00:44:23,871
[ALL YELLING AND GRUNTING]

559
00:45:47,663 --> 00:45:48,747
[SIGHS]

560
00:46:30,622 --> 00:46:31,373
What are you doing here?

561
00:46:31,623 --> 00:46:35,127
A man's responsibility
is to protect his family and his nation.

562
00:46:35,377 --> 00:46:38,338
- Who told you this?
- My father.

563
00:47:12,789 --> 00:47:13,832
[GROANING]

564
00:47:41,777 --> 00:47:44,780
You see how Themistokles
employs deception with such grace?

565
00:47:45,280 --> 00:47:48,200
- Why is it so much to ask for victory?
- How can I make amends?

566
00:47:48,450 --> 00:47:49,826
Silence.

567
00:47:53,246 --> 00:47:55,624
You will carry a message for me.

568
00:47:56,708 --> 00:47:58,126
MAN:
<i>Now they will fear us!</i>

569
00:47:58,377 --> 00:48:02,005
Now they will fear
the Greek men-at-arms! Hup!

570
00:48:03,590 --> 00:48:04,591
THEMISTOKLES:
He's right.

571
00:48:05,342 --> 00:48:07,219
Fear the Greek fighting man.

572
00:48:07,469 --> 00:48:08,595
Fear his sword.

573
00:48:08,845 --> 00:48:10,180
His shield.

574
00:48:10,639 --> 00:48:13,225
Fear his love for Mother Greece.

575
00:48:13,475 --> 00:48:14,976
But most of all...

576
00:48:15,560 --> 00:48:17,187
...fear his freedom!

577
00:48:17,437 --> 00:48:19,564
[ALL CHEERING]

578
00:48:23,276 --> 00:48:25,195
Don't be angry with the boy.

579
00:48:25,487 --> 00:48:26,780
I took him under my command.

580
00:48:27,030 --> 00:48:30,033
Anger is something I reserve
for my enemies.

581
00:48:38,291 --> 00:48:39,876
Themistokles.

582
00:49:00,188 --> 00:49:03,900
Artemisia's ship is being anchored
in neutral waters.

583
00:49:04,151 --> 00:49:06,319
She'd like to meet with Themistokles.

584
00:49:06,570 --> 00:49:09,448
- How can you guarantee his safe return?
ARTAPHERNES: Well, boy...

585
00:49:09,698 --> 00:49:11,616
...the only honor for her now...

586
00:49:11,867 --> 00:49:15,245
...will be when she watches
your crushed and broken fleet...

587
00:49:15,495 --> 00:49:17,414
...sinking to the bottom of the Aegean...

588
00:49:17,664 --> 00:49:19,249
...and is able to recognize you...

589
00:49:19,499 --> 00:49:22,586
...nailed to the mast of your ship
with her sword...

590
00:49:22,836 --> 00:49:25,589
...as you descend to a watery grave.

591
00:49:30,969 --> 00:49:33,472
Why didn't you just say that to begin with?

592
00:50:00,916 --> 00:50:03,418
ARTEMISIA:
Welcome to my humble barge.

593
00:50:03,668 --> 00:50:06,213
We are honored by your presence.

594
00:50:08,673 --> 00:50:10,926
Your barge and you...

595
00:50:11,635 --> 00:50:13,261
...are quite impressive.

596
00:50:18,058 --> 00:50:19,893
Kind words.

597
00:50:21,520 --> 00:50:24,731
Now come, Themistokles.
We have much to discuss.

598
00:50:26,441 --> 00:50:29,110
Do you believe the Greeks
are descended from the gods?

599
00:50:29,361 --> 00:50:30,946
I have heard some say that.

600
00:50:31,196 --> 00:50:34,491
And what of you?
Is there a god in your lineage?

601
00:50:34,741 --> 00:50:38,161
My men say so, and based on
the last two days' battle...

602
00:50:38,662 --> 00:50:41,915
...I'd say there's a spark of the divine in you.

603
00:50:43,124 --> 00:50:45,710
Now who's using kind words?

604
00:50:52,592 --> 00:50:54,177
My men also say that it was you...

605
00:50:54,427 --> 00:50:57,597
...who slayed the good King Darius
at Marathon.

606
00:50:57,847 --> 00:51:00,267
Many heroic deeds occurred on that day.

607
00:51:00,517 --> 00:51:02,227
But it was 10 years ago...

608
00:51:02,477 --> 00:51:04,980
...and the facts of battle
are often embellished.

609
00:51:05,230 --> 00:51:07,065
This deed, you would remember.

610
00:51:08,400 --> 00:51:11,528
I do what I must to defend Greece.

611
00:51:11,778 --> 00:51:14,322
And I do what I must to defeat her.

612
00:51:17,450 --> 00:51:20,453
For every one Greek killed,
you must kill a thousand Persians.

613
00:51:22,455 --> 00:51:24,124
For every ship I sink...

614
00:51:25,083 --> 00:51:26,876
...you must sink a hundred.

615
00:51:27,877 --> 00:51:29,879
I can sustain losses for weeks.

616
00:51:30,130 --> 00:51:32,424
Months, if need be.

617
00:51:32,674 --> 00:51:34,175
My numbers will defeat you...

618
00:51:34,426 --> 00:51:37,137
...and I will take your precious boats
with my sword.

619
00:51:37,387 --> 00:51:38,972
I will take your Greek freedom.

620
00:51:39,681 --> 00:51:42,517
Are you asking me
to negotiate a surrender?

621
00:51:42,767 --> 00:51:43,810
No.

622
00:51:44,811 --> 00:51:47,772
I offer you a chance
to avoid such misery and join me.

623
00:51:49,357 --> 00:51:51,901
I'm in need of a commander such as you.

624
00:51:52,902 --> 00:51:54,529
Look at the defense you've mounted.

625
00:51:56,573 --> 00:51:58,033
A handful of triremes.

626
00:51:58,867 --> 00:52:01,077
Leonidas with 300 Spartans.

627
00:52:01,328 --> 00:52:02,621
[CHUCKLES]

628
00:52:02,871 --> 00:52:04,080
It's insulting, frankly...

629
00:52:04,331 --> 00:52:07,459
...that the mightiest empire the world
has ever seen is met by this.

630
00:52:09,628 --> 00:52:11,796
I don't blame you, Themistokles.

631
00:52:12,631 --> 00:52:15,383
You fought as if the blood
of Poseidon himself...

632
00:52:15,634 --> 00:52:17,761
...was coursing through your veins.

633
00:52:18,011 --> 00:52:19,929
No, I blame Greece.

634
00:52:20,847 --> 00:52:23,850
The squabbling bureaucrats
protecting their political hides...

635
00:52:24,100 --> 00:52:26,978
...by sending you here to die.

636
00:52:30,357 --> 00:52:32,651
And yet you still fight.

637
00:52:34,235 --> 00:52:36,029
So there must be...

638
00:52:37,697 --> 00:52:38,990
What?

639
00:52:40,325 --> 00:52:44,329
Family back home in Athens
that compels you...

640
00:52:45,413 --> 00:52:48,041
...to battle with such passion?

641
00:52:50,293 --> 00:52:52,879
Truth is, I've had no time for family.

642
00:52:53,129 --> 00:52:55,590
I have spent my entire adult life...

643
00:52:55,840 --> 00:52:57,634
...with my one true love...

644
00:52:58,593 --> 00:53:00,178
...the Greek fleet...

645
00:53:00,929 --> 00:53:02,764
...and my one passion...

646
00:53:03,014 --> 00:53:04,891
...readying it for you.

647
00:53:06,518 --> 00:53:08,228
[LAUGHS]

648
00:53:09,062 --> 00:53:10,563
Now, that brings me pleasure...

649
00:53:10,814 --> 00:53:14,275
...the thought of you pining away for me...

650
00:53:15,193 --> 00:53:17,779
...forsaking family and love...

651
00:53:18,029 --> 00:53:21,199
...for the promise of a deeper ecstasy.

652
00:53:28,248 --> 00:53:31,668
The ecstasy of steel and flesh...

653
00:53:32,836 --> 00:53:35,797
...death and life...

654
00:53:37,632 --> 00:53:39,175
...of rage...

655
00:53:40,051 --> 00:53:42,387
...and sweat of muscle...

656
00:53:43,513 --> 00:53:45,432
...of pure joy...

657
00:53:46,433 --> 00:53:48,601
...and deepest sorrow.

658
00:53:49,853 --> 00:53:53,690
Die with me each night and be born again
with me each morning...

659
00:53:54,357 --> 00:53:58,236
...as you plant your sword
into the hearts of our enemies.

660
00:54:01,990 --> 00:54:03,658
You fight for freedom.

661
00:54:04,200 --> 00:54:07,954
I offer freedom without
consequence or responsibility.

662
00:54:11,207 --> 00:54:12,667
Join me...

663
00:54:14,127 --> 00:54:15,837
...at my side.

664
00:54:16,129 --> 00:54:20,133
Breathe each breath with me
as if it were your last.

665
00:54:39,235 --> 00:54:40,904
[PANTING]

666
00:54:48,495 --> 00:54:50,330
[ARTEMISIA GRUNTING]

667
00:54:55,460 --> 00:54:56,503
[GRUNTING]

668
00:55:15,939 --> 00:55:17,941
[ARTEMISIA & THEMISTOKLES
GRUNTING]

669
00:55:30,245 --> 00:55:31,955
[MOANS]

670
00:56:09,200 --> 00:56:10,702
Join me.

671
00:56:16,749 --> 00:56:17,959
No.

672
00:56:22,297 --> 00:56:23,381
[BOTH GRUNTING]

673
00:56:29,095 --> 00:56:32,348
You're no god. You're just a man.

674
00:56:47,488 --> 00:56:49,741
Be quick with your sword.

675
00:56:53,202 --> 00:56:55,413
You'll not have your death tonight.

676
00:56:55,955 --> 00:56:57,123
Guards!

677
00:56:58,750 --> 00:57:00,919
Remove this filth from my ship.

678
00:57:04,923 --> 00:57:06,132
[YELLS THEN SWORD CLANGS]

679
00:57:27,195 --> 00:57:27,946
AESKYLOS:
Well?

680
00:57:28,905 --> 00:57:30,782
What have you learned?

681
00:57:32,033 --> 00:57:33,910
[SIGHS]

682
00:57:38,122 --> 00:57:40,083
Can Artemisia be beaten?

683
00:57:41,793 --> 00:57:44,087
The next time that we face her...

684
00:57:44,337 --> 00:57:46,965
...she's going to bring all of hell with her.

685
00:57:47,215 --> 00:57:49,050
[SIGHS]

686
00:58:40,893 --> 00:58:43,312
Hold! Hold!

687
00:58:54,866 --> 00:58:56,951
Send in my personal guard.

688
00:59:23,853 --> 00:59:24,854
Pull back!

689
00:59:25,104 --> 00:59:26,189
Retreat!

690
00:59:26,439 --> 00:59:27,565
MAN: Retreat!
SCYLLIAS: Retreat!

691
00:59:27,815 --> 00:59:29,317
MAN: Retreat!
SCYLLIAS: Retreat!

692
00:59:30,026 --> 00:59:31,736
Themistokles!

693
00:59:31,986 --> 00:59:33,488
In the water!

694
00:59:37,033 --> 00:59:39,202
Archers on deck now!

695
00:59:39,452 --> 00:59:41,120
SCYLLIAS:
Archers on deck now! Quickly!

696
00:59:41,704 --> 00:59:42,830
THEMISTOKLES:
Starboard side!

697
00:59:43,081 --> 00:59:44,248
Fire at will!

698
00:59:51,714 --> 00:59:53,716
[YELLING]

699
01:00:02,433 --> 01:00:03,643
[GRUNTING]

700
01:00:22,453 --> 01:00:23,913
[ARROW PIERCES FLESH]

701
01:00:57,780 --> 01:00:59,282
[GASPS]

702
01:01:00,908 --> 01:01:02,201
Fight on, boy.

703
01:01:02,451 --> 01:01:03,494
Uh-huh.

704
01:01:03,744 --> 01:01:05,204
SCYLLIAS:
Fight on!

705
01:01:06,998 --> 01:01:08,958
[WHOOSHING IN DISTANCE]

706
01:01:13,504 --> 01:01:14,714
[ALL YELLING]

707
01:01:25,016 --> 01:01:26,726
THEMISTOKLES:
Aim for the men on top!

708
01:01:26,976 --> 01:01:28,186
Up there!

709
01:02:38,714 --> 01:02:41,550
Abandon ship! Abandon ship!

710
01:02:41,801 --> 01:02:43,761
Abandon ship!

711
01:04:11,140 --> 01:04:12,099
[GRUNTS]

712
01:04:29,533 --> 01:04:31,869
GORGO:
<i>The dead have no guilt.</i>

713
01:04:32,411 --> 01:04:34,622
<i>No responsibility.</i>

714
01:04:35,831 --> 01:04:38,000
<i>Themistokles watches the bodies
of his men...</i>

715
01:04:38,250 --> 01:04:41,087
<i>...turn the Aegean red with blood.</i>

716
01:04:42,129 --> 01:04:43,964
<i>Were they sacrificed for his ego?</i>

717
01:04:45,674 --> 01:04:49,678
<i>Or to relieve the guilt of the long-ago
mistake at Marathon?</i>

718
01:04:52,681 --> 01:04:54,392
<i>How many men would have been saved...</i>

719
01:04:54,642 --> 01:04:57,603
<i>...if Themistokles had killed that boy?</i>

720
01:05:00,356 --> 01:05:03,109
<i>Not even his own soul can be sure.</i>

721
01:05:04,568 --> 01:05:06,195
My friend.

722
01:05:07,113 --> 01:05:09,073
We faced the odds.

723
01:05:10,408 --> 01:05:11,992
[IN STRAINED VOICE]
Together.

724
01:05:13,994 --> 01:05:14,995
Listen to me...

725
01:05:15,246 --> 01:05:17,123
...Themistokles.

726
01:05:20,709 --> 01:05:22,878
You will have to fight...

727
01:05:23,129 --> 01:05:25,923
...with twice as much strength
in the morning.

728
01:05:26,799 --> 01:05:28,801
We will fight shoulder-to-shoulder.

729
01:05:29,051 --> 01:05:30,428
SCYLLIAS:
No, my son.

730
01:05:31,887 --> 01:05:34,640
You will carry on for both of us.

731
01:05:48,446 --> 01:05:50,448
[SCYLLIAS WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

732
01:06:21,437 --> 01:06:23,439
[SOBBING]

733
01:06:33,949 --> 01:06:35,367
What did he say?

734
01:06:37,912 --> 01:06:40,164
I will tell you in time, boy.

735
01:06:42,416 --> 01:06:43,751
Quiet now.

736
01:06:45,085 --> 01:06:47,505
You go and be with your father's spirit.

737
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:59,433
How many times do you think
we will repeat such a tragedy?

738
01:07:00,976 --> 01:07:02,144
As many times as we must.

739
01:07:03,229 --> 01:07:05,064
We are turning young men into memories.

740
01:07:08,692 --> 01:07:10,611
Do you think I enjoy this?

741
01:07:12,154 --> 01:07:14,156
Witnessing my friend's final breath?

742
01:07:18,077 --> 01:07:20,412
Every widow that is made by my decision...

743
01:07:22,498 --> 01:07:25,209
...every child that will grow
without a father...

744
01:07:27,002 --> 01:07:28,754
...they are my choices.

745
01:07:29,755 --> 01:07:33,384
This is the burden of my command.

746
01:07:48,899 --> 01:07:50,109
[SQUAWKS]

747
01:07:57,283 --> 01:07:58,909
XERXES:
How easy it is to silence...

748
01:07:59,159 --> 01:08:02,371
...the strong and self-disciplined.

749
01:08:02,621 --> 01:08:05,791
Let my army witness
the great warriors of Sparta.

750
01:08:09,044 --> 01:08:12,214
March them past these corpses.

751
01:08:12,464 --> 01:08:15,634
Let them see the cost
of daring to challenge the god-king.

752
01:08:19,388 --> 01:08:20,931
King Leonidas...

753
01:08:21,181 --> 01:08:25,185
...and his brave 300
were the finest Greece has to offer.

754
01:08:25,477 --> 01:08:26,729
There will be no saviors...

755
01:08:26,979 --> 01:08:29,398
...to rise up and vanquish us.

756
01:08:30,024 --> 01:08:32,818
Nothing will stop the march of my empire.

757
01:08:35,362 --> 01:08:36,530
EPHIALTES:
Your Majesty.

758
01:08:39,366 --> 01:08:41,327
XERXES:
You, take this dead king's sword...

759
01:08:41,577 --> 01:08:42,870
...to Athens.

760
01:08:43,120 --> 01:08:46,040
Let them know
that I am coming next for them.

761
01:08:47,207 --> 01:08:48,792
Let them know...

762
01:08:49,043 --> 01:08:50,544
...Athens...

763
01:08:51,253 --> 01:08:54,131
...their prize jewel of a city...

764
01:08:54,923 --> 01:08:57,343
...will disappear from the histories.

765
01:09:01,013 --> 01:09:02,431
Themistokles!

766
01:09:05,517 --> 01:09:06,518
I bring word...

767
01:09:06,769 --> 01:09:09,396
...from Thermopylae.
Leonidas was betrayed by a hunchback.

768
01:09:09,647 --> 01:09:11,315
The Spartans have been slaughtered.

769
01:09:11,565 --> 01:09:12,775
The Hot Gates have fallen.

770
01:09:15,778 --> 01:09:17,821
Such a sacrifice.

771
01:09:21,950 --> 01:09:24,119
Now Greece has her martyrs.

772
01:09:25,371 --> 01:09:27,539
Daxos, take that message...

773
01:09:27,790 --> 01:09:29,333
...from the Hot Gates...

774
01:09:29,583 --> 01:09:31,919
...to every city, every village.

775
01:09:32,169 --> 01:09:34,755
Let every countryman hear your words.

776
01:09:35,005 --> 01:09:36,799
But they are dead. All of them.

777
01:09:37,049 --> 01:09:39,843
Sparta's sacrifice will be what unites us.

778
01:09:40,427 --> 01:09:41,804
Now go.

779
01:09:43,055 --> 01:09:43,639
DAXOS:
Hyah!

780
01:09:43,889 --> 01:09:46,600
Move all of our ships and men back
to the safety of Salamis.

781
01:09:46,850 --> 01:09:48,227
And you?

782
01:09:49,061 --> 01:09:51,313
I will take Daxos' message to Athens.

783
01:09:52,523 --> 01:09:55,776
THEMISTOKLES: I was told a hunchback
was accountable for the fall of the Hot Gates.

784
01:09:57,194 --> 01:10:00,280
That he sold out his country...

785
01:10:00,531 --> 01:10:03,742
...pulled the crimson from his back
and replaced it with Persian gold.

786
01:10:06,495 --> 01:10:08,288
What is your name, traitor?

787
01:10:09,373 --> 01:10:12,501
Ephialtes of Trachis.

788
01:10:24,430 --> 01:10:28,434
I should wet this noble blade
with your blood.

789
01:10:30,185 --> 01:10:32,020
You would be right to do so.

790
01:10:32,855 --> 01:10:35,524
There is little beauty about me.

791
01:10:35,774 --> 01:10:39,778
There is little beauty in what I have done.

792
01:10:44,616 --> 01:10:46,285
Say what you must.

793
01:10:46,952 --> 01:10:48,787
I beg of you...

794
01:10:49,371 --> 01:10:50,873
...and all of Athens!

795
01:10:51,123 --> 01:10:54,668
The god-king will burn this city
to the ground!

796
01:10:54,918 --> 01:10:55,961
MAN:
What does he mean?

797
01:10:56,503 --> 01:10:58,172
THEMISTOKLES:
Quiet yourselves!

798
01:10:59,131 --> 01:11:03,135
Leonidas' and Sparta's great sacrifice
was no defeat.

799
01:11:06,263 --> 01:11:08,348
It was a beautiful victory.

800
01:11:11,643 --> 01:11:14,104
This simple act of valor...

801
01:11:14,396 --> 01:11:16,857
...will allow us to rally each
of our city-states...

802
01:11:17,107 --> 01:11:19,109
...and unite Greece...

803
01:11:19,985 --> 01:11:21,987
...for one purpose...

804
01:11:22,321 --> 01:11:23,489
...against one enemy!

805
01:11:24,907 --> 01:11:25,949
And you.

806
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:29,453
You take this message to your god-king.

807
01:11:29,703 --> 01:11:32,247
That we will take whatever ships
we have left...

808
01:11:32,790 --> 01:11:35,250
...and finish this in the Bay of Salamis.

809
01:11:36,126 --> 01:11:38,712
But there will be death and destruction.

810
01:11:38,962 --> 01:11:42,758
Yes, there will be.

811
01:11:44,718 --> 01:11:45,511
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

812
01:11:49,515 --> 01:11:50,933
Themistokles.

813
01:11:53,268 --> 01:11:55,437
I'm here to speak to your queen.

814
01:11:56,188 --> 01:11:57,689
A warning, Athenian.

815
01:11:57,940 --> 01:12:00,692
You may not receive a warm welcome.

816
01:12:27,469 --> 01:12:30,055
May I offer my deepest sympathies.

817
01:12:31,682 --> 01:12:34,518
I cannot change what has happened
to Leonidas...

818
01:12:34,768 --> 01:12:37,604
...but his sacrifice will not be forgotten.

819
01:12:38,564 --> 01:12:42,025
Do not lecture me on sacrifice,
and be quick with your words, Athenian.

820
01:12:44,903 --> 01:12:48,156
I request of you the entire Spartan navy.

821
01:12:48,907 --> 01:12:50,492
Every man, every ship...

822
01:12:50,742 --> 01:12:53,078
- ...that you can spare.
- Have I not given enough...

823
01:12:53,328 --> 01:12:54,997
...for your dream of a united Greece?

824
01:12:55,372 --> 01:12:58,750
Shall I put swords in the hands
of my son? Our children?

825
01:12:59,001 --> 01:13:00,210
Would that please you?

826
01:13:01,670 --> 01:13:05,173
Have I not given enough
for your ambitions, Themistokles?

827
01:13:05,424 --> 01:13:06,967
A king.

828
01:13:07,676 --> 01:13:10,053
Husbands, fathers, brothers.

829
01:13:10,304 --> 01:13:12,764
Sparta will give no more.

830
01:13:28,447 --> 01:13:29,990
This belongs with you.

831
01:13:40,250 --> 01:13:41,710
Avenge him.

832
01:13:59,686 --> 01:14:02,439
GORGO:
<i>The Oracle's words stood as a warning.</i>

833
01:14:03,190 --> 01:14:05,108
<i>All of Greece will fall...</i>

834
01:14:05,734 --> 01:14:09,029
<i>...as Persian fire reduces Athens to cinder.</i>

835
01:14:10,489 --> 01:14:12,824
<i>For Athens is a pile of stone and wood...</i>

836
01:14:13,075 --> 01:14:15,661
<i>...and cloth and dust...</i>

837
01:14:16,578 --> 01:14:19,373
<i>...and, as dust, will vanish into the wind.</i>

838
01:14:21,041 --> 01:14:23,835
<i>Only the Athenians themselves exist.</i>

839
01:14:25,045 --> 01:14:28,632
<i>And the fate of the world
hangs on their every syllable.</i>

840
01:14:29,508 --> 01:14:31,885
<i>Only the Athenians exist.</i>

841
01:14:32,260 --> 01:14:35,222
<i>And only stout wooden ships can save them.</i>

842
01:14:35,889 --> 01:14:37,474
<i>Wooden ships...</i>

843
01:14:38,266 --> 01:14:41,103
<i>...and a tidal wave of heroes' blood.</i>

844
01:14:48,193 --> 01:14:51,279
XERXES:
The Greeks were fools to stand against us.

845
01:14:51,530 --> 01:14:53,156
Leonidas and his pride...

846
01:14:53,407 --> 01:14:55,993
...were no match for the will of a god.

847
01:14:58,286 --> 01:15:02,207
Themistokles was a worthless coward.

848
01:15:02,457 --> 01:15:03,959
And now...

849
01:15:04,501 --> 01:15:08,213
...this pathetic navy
is barely worth our attention.

850
01:15:08,463 --> 01:15:10,757
If that worthless coward
had stood at my side...

851
01:15:11,008 --> 01:15:12,592
...we would have laid the world...

852
01:15:12,843 --> 01:15:13,927
...at your feet.

853
01:15:14,845 --> 01:15:15,971
EPHIALTES:
My king.

854
01:15:17,180 --> 01:15:20,684
Your humble servant brings you news.

855
01:15:22,019 --> 01:15:24,396
The Greek fleet are defenseless...

856
01:15:24,646 --> 01:15:26,815
...within the Bay of Salamis.

857
01:15:27,482 --> 01:15:29,943
You need only finish them.

858
01:15:30,861 --> 01:15:32,529
Who commands their forces?

859
01:15:36,033 --> 01:15:38,535
Themistokles of Athens.

860
01:15:38,785 --> 01:15:40,620
Themistokles is dead.

861
01:15:40,871 --> 01:15:44,332
EPHIALTES:
He is alive. I have seen him myself.

862
01:15:58,638 --> 01:16:00,432
ARTEMISIA:
Ready my troops and armor.

863
01:16:00,682 --> 01:16:01,975
We will attack at once.

864
01:16:02,225 --> 01:16:03,226
Wisdom...

865
01:16:04,936 --> 01:16:05,687
...would have us...

866
01:16:05,937 --> 01:16:08,607
...send a probing force to confirm
it is not a trap.

867
01:16:09,775 --> 01:16:12,027
You would dare to advise me
in matters of war?

868
01:16:13,653 --> 01:16:15,572
I am the god-king.

869
01:16:15,822 --> 01:16:18,533
I am the one who triumphed over Leonidas.

870
01:16:18,784 --> 01:16:20,827
I am the one who laid waste...

871
01:16:21,078 --> 01:16:22,871
...to this showpiece of Athens.

872
01:16:23,121 --> 01:16:26,291
- I am your king.
ARTEMISIA: Killing Leonidas and his men...

873
01:16:26,541 --> 01:16:28,710
...only made them martyrs.

874
01:16:29,586 --> 01:16:31,588
And when you razed Athens...

875
01:16:32,214 --> 01:16:33,882
...you set fire to the only thing...

876
01:16:34,132 --> 01:16:36,051
...of value in this country.

877
01:16:48,063 --> 01:16:50,482
I will attack the Greeks...

878
01:16:51,650 --> 01:16:54,236
...with my entire navy.

879
01:16:55,445 --> 01:16:56,571
Artemisia.

880
01:16:56,822 --> 01:16:58,156
Enough!

881
01:16:59,658 --> 01:17:03,036
Do not forget who put the crown
on your childish head.

882
01:17:03,620 --> 01:17:05,247
My king.

883
01:17:06,331 --> 01:17:07,833
Now sit on your golden throne...

884
01:17:08,083 --> 01:17:10,752
...and watch this battle
from the safety I provide you.

885
01:17:17,050 --> 01:17:18,718
THEMISTOKLES:
There in the distance...

886
01:17:19,928 --> 01:17:22,681
...we witness the destruction of Athens.

887
01:17:26,226 --> 01:17:30,230
Alone, we will face the monster
that cast a shadow across our land.

888
01:17:33,316 --> 01:17:36,945
I had prayed that the Spartans
would come to lend a hand this morning.

889
01:17:39,990 --> 01:17:41,908
Perhaps they feel they have given enough.

890
01:17:42,159 --> 01:17:43,577
COMMANDER 1:
You failed us all.

891
01:17:43,827 --> 01:17:45,203
This is your fault, Themistokles.

892
01:17:45,453 --> 01:17:47,038
Without Spartans, we're farmhands.

893
01:17:47,289 --> 01:17:49,332
COMMANDER 2: We should've negotiated
with the Persians when we had the chance.

894
01:17:54,254 --> 01:17:55,964
You are all right.

895
01:17:57,799 --> 01:18:01,553
Yes, we are down to a handful of boats.

896
01:18:02,637 --> 01:18:06,099
And, yes, we are just farmhands.

897
01:18:06,808 --> 01:18:08,560
We are tradesmen.

898
01:18:09,686 --> 01:18:10,770
We are boys...

899
01:18:11,438 --> 01:18:15,150
...turned to men through the sacrifice
and forge of combat.

900
01:18:17,611 --> 01:18:19,946
I played a dangerous game...

901
01:18:20,197 --> 01:18:21,781
...and I lost!

902
01:18:26,661 --> 01:18:29,998
If you choose to turn your back on me...

903
01:18:30,457 --> 01:18:31,833
...on your country...

904
01:18:35,128 --> 01:18:37,047
...I will not judge you.

905
01:18:38,715 --> 01:18:40,759
You are free to leave.

906
01:18:41,843 --> 01:18:43,637
You are still free men.

907
01:19:07,077 --> 01:19:08,245
Very well.

908
01:19:10,163 --> 01:19:11,164
Then let us...

909
01:19:11,414 --> 01:19:15,377
...put our shoulders to work
and free those ships from the bosom of Greece.

910
01:19:17,712 --> 01:19:20,382
Today is a privilege to call our own.

911
01:19:21,716 --> 01:19:25,303
A story that will be told
for a thousand years.

912
01:19:26,471 --> 01:19:28,473
Let our final stand...

913
01:19:28,723 --> 01:19:30,767
...be recorded to the histories.

914
01:19:31,226 --> 01:19:33,019
And let it be shown...

915
01:19:33,603 --> 01:19:36,189
...that we chose to die on our feet...

916
01:19:36,439 --> 01:19:38,692
...rather than live on our knees!

917
01:19:38,942 --> 01:19:40,944
[ALL CHEERING]

918
01:20:26,906 --> 01:20:29,284
There is only one thing
you need to know today.

919
01:20:29,534 --> 01:20:31,036
Not to get killed.

920
01:20:31,286 --> 01:20:35,290
No. Your father's last words.

921
01:20:39,377 --> 01:20:42,422
He told me that you had earned
the right to sit at the table.

922
01:20:59,689 --> 01:21:03,693
Well, my brother,
I have no more tactics or tricks.

923
01:21:05,487 --> 01:21:07,864
This will be the last battle that we share.

924
01:21:08,114 --> 01:21:11,743
We have fought next to one other
for as long as I can remember.

925
01:21:12,577 --> 01:21:15,955
Nothing would please me more
than to rest this sword.

926
01:21:17,123 --> 01:21:20,710
- The preparations that are required?
- Below deck.

927
01:21:21,795 --> 01:21:23,713
- Good.
- Are you sure...

928
01:21:23,963 --> 01:21:25,757
...that you want to commit everything?

929
01:21:26,466 --> 01:21:27,550
Yes.

930
01:21:29,386 --> 01:21:32,263
<i>Without Artemisia's command,
the Persian navy is nothing.</i>

931
01:21:34,015 --> 01:21:36,142
AESKYLOS:
<i>We will never be able to reach her.</i>

932
01:21:36,393 --> 01:21:37,936
THEMISTOKLES:
<i>I will reach her...</i>

933
01:21:38,728 --> 01:21:40,647
<i>...and put an end to this.</i>

934
01:21:41,564 --> 01:21:43,983
There will be no room for a retreat.

935
01:21:45,402 --> 01:21:46,820
I know.

936
01:21:49,197 --> 01:21:52,617
ARTEMISIA:
<i>Today the last Greek ships will be destroyed.</i>

937
01:21:52,867 --> 01:21:54,953
<i>Show them no mercy.</i>

938
01:21:55,203 --> 01:21:57,705
<i>Give them no quarter.</i>

939
01:21:57,956 --> 01:22:01,167
Today we will dance across the backs
of dead Greeks.

940
01:22:01,876 --> 01:22:04,629
<i>Today we deliver submission.</i>

941
01:22:05,505 --> 01:22:07,549
Today I want to feel Themistokles' throat...

942
01:22:07,841 --> 01:22:09,801
...beneath my boots.

943
01:22:28,862 --> 01:22:30,280
[MEN YELLING]

944
01:22:40,623 --> 01:22:43,084
Men, brace yourselves!

945
01:23:37,222 --> 01:23:38,806
Prepare for close quarters.

946
01:23:39,057 --> 01:23:40,558
Attack!

947
01:23:40,808 --> 01:23:42,519
[MEN YELLING]

948
01:23:46,689 --> 01:23:47,815
Your father watches you!

949
01:23:49,192 --> 01:23:51,361
Hold nothing back!

950
01:23:51,611 --> 01:23:52,946
Seize your glory!

951
01:23:58,284 --> 01:24:00,286
[ALL GRUNTING]

952
01:24:13,675 --> 01:24:14,676
[YELLS]

953
01:24:21,307 --> 01:24:23,851
I'm not here as a witness.

954
01:24:28,940 --> 01:24:30,400
[ALL YELLING AND GRUNTING]

955
01:24:41,869 --> 01:24:42,870
[MAN GASPING]

956
01:25:25,788 --> 01:25:26,623
Now!

957
01:25:27,415 --> 01:25:30,043
And let them send our souls straight to hell!

958
01:25:30,293 --> 01:25:31,711
[HORSE NEIGHING]

959
01:26:07,622 --> 01:26:10,166
Hyah! Come on!

960
01:26:21,427 --> 01:26:22,720
[THEMISTOKLES YELLS]

961
01:27:16,899 --> 01:27:18,443
You offered freedom without...

962
01:27:18,693 --> 01:27:21,654
- ...consequence or responsibility.
- Are you accepting my offer?

963
01:27:21,904 --> 01:27:23,364
My answer is still no.

964
01:27:51,976 --> 01:27:54,353
You fight much harder than you fuck.

965
01:28:07,867 --> 01:28:08,701
[THEMISTOKLES SCREAMS]

966
01:28:37,897 --> 01:28:40,566
Surrender to me or meet your death.

967
01:28:40,817 --> 01:28:41,943
Who would you fight...

968
01:28:42,193 --> 01:28:43,444
...if not for me?

969
01:28:44,070 --> 01:28:46,280
No one could challenge your skill.

970
01:28:46,531 --> 01:28:49,492
I would rather die a free man than as a slave.

971
01:28:50,618 --> 01:28:53,079
Even if the chain was attached to you.

972
01:29:02,213 --> 01:29:04,674
GORGO:
<i>It begins as a whisper.</i>

973
01:29:05,466 --> 01:29:07,093
<i>A promise.</i>

974
01:29:08,135 --> 01:29:09,470
<i>The lightest of breezes...</i>

975
01:29:09,720 --> 01:29:10,972
<i>...dances through the rigging...</i>

976
01:29:11,222 --> 01:29:14,308
<i>...as it creaks above the death cries
of 10,000 men.</i>

977
01:29:15,685 --> 01:29:19,272
<i>It moves through her hair
as gently as a lover's hand.</i>

978
01:29:19,772 --> 01:29:20,648
<i>That breeze...</i>

979
01:29:21,941 --> 01:29:25,778
<i>...that promise, became a wind,
a wind that is blown across Greece...</i>

980
01:29:26,028 --> 01:29:28,489
<i>...carrying a message told again and again...</i>

981
01:29:28,739 --> 01:29:31,701
<i>...of our Lady Freedom
and how wise she was...</i>

982
01:29:31,951 --> 01:29:35,705
<i>...to charge Leonidas to lay all at her feet.</i>

983
01:29:37,373 --> 01:29:40,251
A wind, my brothers, of sacrifice.

984
01:29:42,128 --> 01:29:44,046
A wind of freedom.

985
01:29:46,257 --> 01:29:48,426
A wind of justice.

986
01:29:56,100 --> 01:29:58,144
A wind of vengeance.

987
01:30:21,042 --> 01:30:22,793
MEN [IN UNISON]:
Ah-ooh! Ah-ooh! Ah-ooh!

988
01:30:23,044 --> 01:30:25,046
[MEN CONTINUE CHANTING]

989
01:30:40,269 --> 01:30:41,437
[ARTEMISIA GRUNTS]

990
01:30:42,605 --> 01:30:43,856
You are being surrounded.

991
01:30:44,357 --> 01:30:47,276
All of Greece has united against you.

992
01:30:47,902 --> 01:30:50,821
<i>Delphi, Thebes, Olympia...</i>

993
01:30:51,072 --> 01:30:53,866
<i>...Arcadia and Sparta.</i>

994
01:31:08,214 --> 01:31:10,758
If death comes for me today, I'm ready.

995
01:31:12,051 --> 01:31:14,053
I could lower my sword.

996
01:31:14,303 --> 01:31:16,973
There's still time for you
to ready a launch and escape.

997
01:31:21,268 --> 01:31:24,855
It would be a poor choice
to force my hand into action.

998
01:31:25,481 --> 01:31:29,193
Now order your ships to disengage
and surrender to me.

999
01:31:31,612 --> 01:31:33,280
Surrender?

1000
01:31:39,203 --> 01:31:40,204
[GROANS]

1001
01:31:43,916 --> 01:31:45,376
